[{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","text":"Documentation for MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","category":"section"},{"location":"#Sources","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"Sources","text":"git clone git@gitlab.inria.fr:mingus/code-vp-multistream.git\ncd code-vp-multistream","category":"section"},{"location":"#Install-and-Run","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"Install and Run","text":"julia\njulia> import Pkg\njulia> Pkg.update() # update your Julia setup\njulia> Pkg.add(\"Plots\") # Install the plot library\njulia> Pkg.activate(pwd()) # Activate the local environment\njulia> Pkg.instantiate() # Install package dependencies\njulia> include(\"examples/landau_damping.jl\") # Run the example","category":"section"},{"location":"#Example","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"Example","text":"using MultiPhaseVlasov\nusing Plots\n\neps = 1.0\nnx = 200\nk = 0.5\nxmin, xmax = 0.0, 2π / k\nvmin, vmax = -6.0, 6.0\nng = 200\nmesh = UniformMesh(xmin, xmax, nx)","category":"section"},{"location":"#Functions","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.GaussHermiteGrid","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.GaussHermiteGrid","text":"struct GaussHermiteGrid <: MultiPhaseVlasov.AbstractGrid\n\nGenerate the grid in velocity to approach the measure dmu_0 by an empirical measure With Gauss-Hermite, points in velocity are using Gauss-Hermite quadrature\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.TwoStreams","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.TwoStreams","text":"struct TwoStreams\n\nThe Two-Stream Distribution Function\n\nThe standard choice is a double-shifted Maxwellian:\n\nf_0(x v) = fracn_02sqrt2piv_th left expleft(-\frac(v - v_0)^22v_th^2\right) \n+ expleft(-frac(v + v_0)^22v_th^2right) right cdot left(1 + epsilon cos(kx)right)\n\nwhere:\n\npm v_0 are the drift velocities of the two beams (equal and opposite)\nv_th is the thermal velocity of each beam\nepsilon ll 1 is the perturbation amplitude (typically epsilon sim 001005)\nk = 2piL is the wavenumber of the perturbation\nL is the domain length\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.UniformGrid","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.UniformGrid","text":"struct UniformGrid <: MultiPhaseVlasov.AbstractGrid\n\nUniform grid in velocity with n points starting \n\nv_l = vmin + (l-1) (vmax-vmin)(n-1)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.G-NTuple{4, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.G","text":"G(s, t, u, dx)\n\n\nFunction G: (s,t,u) –> sg(u) - t(g(u)-u).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.compute_elec_energy-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, MultiPhaseVlasov.AbstractMesh}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.compute_elec_energy","text":"compute_elec_energy(phi, mesh; ϵ)\n\n\nCompute the electric energy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.compute_x_feet_mesh!-Tuple{SemiLagrangian, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.compute_x_feet_mesh!","text":"compute_x_feet_mesh!(solver, u, e, dt)\n\n\nUse Fixed-Point methodod to compute the feet of the characteristic : X(t-dt) = X(t) + d we search for d\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.dg-Tuple{Float64, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.dg","text":"dg(x, dx)\n\n\nNumerical derivative of g using finite differences.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.g-Tuple{Float64, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.g","text":"g(x, dx)\n\n\nRegularization function of (x)^{+}.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.mymax-Tuple{Float64, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.mymax","text":"mymax(a, b)\n\n\nMaximum of two values.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.newton-Tuple{Any}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.newton","text":"newton(r)\n\n\nFunction to construct the Monte Carlo grid based on the inverse of the cumulative distribution function\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.poisson-Tuple{UniformMesh, Vector{Float64}}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.poisson","text":"poisson(mesh, rho; ϵ)\n\n\nSolve the elliptic problem: ϵ^2 Δϕ = ρ-1  on the Torus.\n\nUses Fourier method.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.sample_maxwellian-Tuple{Any, Any, Int64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.sample_maxwellian","text":"sample_maxwellian(vth, v0, nb_sample)\n\n\nFunction to sample a Maxwellian with mean and temperature given\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.solve!-Tuple{Vector{Float64}, NonLinearPoissonSolver, Vector{Float64}}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.solve!","text":"solve!(phi, solver, rho_tot)\n\n\nSolve the quasi-linear elliptic problem: ϵ^2 Δϕ + exp(-ϕ) = ρ on the Torus.\n\nUses Newton's method.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.t_rho-NTuple{4, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.t_rho","text":"t_rho(s, t, u, dx)\n\n\nHelper function for density calculation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.update_rho!-Tuple{MultiPhaseVlasov.AbstractMesh, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Float64}","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.update_rho!","text":"update_rho!(mesh, rho, u, rho_at_step_n, dt)\n\n\nUpdate one single fluid solution using fixed-point iteration.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MultiPhaseVlasov.update_u!","page":"MultiPhaseVlasov.jl","title":"MultiPhaseVlasov.update_u!","text":"update_u!(mesh, rho, u, phi, rho_at_step_n, u_at_step_n, dt)\nupdate_u!(\n    mesh,\n    rho,\n    u,\n    phi,\n    rho_at_step_n,\n    u_at_step_n,\n    dt,\n    maxiter\n)\n\n\nUpdate one single fluid solution using fixed-point iteration.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"}]
